*[toxcore/bin_io.h, line 66 at r1](https://reviewable.io:443/reviews/toktok/c-toxcore/320#-KZQacQkHsY67gfQIiy2:-KZQacQl-vNmEioaPNv-:b-assk4d) ([raw file](https://github.com/toktok/c-toxcore/blob/30dc3974b74a3115e252e3e4f616da7a0eb5a8da/toxcore/bin_io.h#L66)):*
> ```objc
>  * @param initial The initial capacity of the writer.
>  */
> struct Bin_W *bin_w_new(size_t initial, BIN_ERR_NEW *error);
> ```

How about having a constructor that doesn't require specification of the inital capacity?

Current constructor encourages to sum sizes of all things we are going to write, e.g. `bin_w_new(size1 + size2 + SOME_CONSTANT_SIZE*6 +1 +7 + size44 + sizeof(uint64_t), &error);`, which is quite ugly. If the writer automatically resizes internal array, this should really be optional. The default initial capacity could be the maximum toxcore packet size (there is a define for that) or something else if you think that's a bad choice.

