*[toxcore/bin_io.h, line 185 at r1](https://reviewable.io:443/reviews/toktok/c-toxcore/320#-KZQW_oIGfV_gzPspiFf:-KZQW_oIGfV_gzPspiFg:b34cfu6) ([raw file](https://github.com/toktok/c-toxcore/blob/30dc3974b74a3115e252e3e4f616da7a0eb5a8da/toxcore/bin_io.h#L185)):*
> ```objc
>  * Read an 8 bit unsigned integer and advance the reader by 1 byte.
>  */
> uint8_t bin_r_u08(struct Bin_R *r, BIN_ERR_READ *error);
> ```

I think it's more convenient to have the error argument and the return value switched around, the error being changed to bool:

```C
bool bin_r_u08(struct Bin_R *r, uint8_t *dest);
```

That way you can put one or multiple short-circuited writes/reads in a single if-condition to check if the entire write/read succeeded

```C
if (!bin_r_u08(foo, &struct.var1) ||
     !bin_r_u16(foo, &struct.var2)) {
    // reads failed!
}
```

Instead of the mouthful

```C
BIN_ERR_READ error;
struct.var1 = bin_r_u08(foo, &error);
if (error != BIN_ERR_READ_OK) {
    // first read failed
}
struct.var2 = bin_r_u16(foo, &error);
if (error != BIN_ERR_READ_OK) {
    // second read failed
}
```

you can't just check if the entire read/write has failed in short-circuit way without writing all this out.

Though with short circuiting would won't know which exact function call failed, but you might not need to know, and if you do need to know, you can rewrite it as in this `BIN_ERR_READ` example too.

```C
bool success = true;
success &= bin_r_u08(foo, &struct.var1);
if (!success) {
    // first read failed
}
success &= bin_r_u16(foo, &struct.var2);
if (!success) {
    // second read failed
}
```

or if you you don't need short circuiting things

```C
bool success = true;
success &= bin_r_u08(foo, &struct.var1);
success &= bin_r_u16(foo, &struct.var2);
if (!success) {
   ...
}
```

Instead of the mouthful

```C
bool success = true;
BIN_ERR_READ error;
struct.var1 = bin_r_u08(foo, &error);
success &= error == BIN_ERR_READ_OK;
struct.var2 = bin_r_u16(foo, &error);
success &= error == BIN_ERR_READ_OK;
if (!success) {
   ...
}
```

